duloxetine with an incremental cost-effectiveness ratio of $43,437. Other 
comparators were dominated. Key drivers included the rates of cardiovascular and 
gastrointestinal adverse events and proton pump inhibitor usage. In subgroup 
analysis, the incremental cost-effectiveness ratio for duloxetine fell to 
$21,567 for a population 65 years or older and to $18,726 for a population at 
higher risk of cardiovascular and gastrointestinal adverse events.
CONCLUSION: The model estimates that duloxetine is a moderately cost-effective 
treatment for CLBP, becoming more cost-effective for populations older than 65 
years or at greater risk of cardiovascular and gastrointestinal events.
LEVEL OF EVIDENCE: 1.

