[The burden of disease for cancer in Santander, Colombia, 2005].

[Article in Spanish]

Esquiaqui-Felipe R(1), Posso-Valencia H, Peñaloza RE, Rodríguez-García J.

Author information:
(1)Universidad Industrial de Santander, Bucaramanga, Colombia. 
esquiaqui22@hotmail.com

OBJECTIVES: Determining the burden of cancer in Santander using disability 
adjusted life years (DALY).
METHODS: This was a descriptive study of the disease burden for determining 
DALYs caused by cancer in Santander. The unit of analysis consisted of the 
Autonomous University of Bucaramanga- Population-Based Cancer Centre records and 
National Bureau of Statistics- mortality records for 2005.
RESULTS: The global burden of disease for Santander was estimated at 877 DALY 
per hundred thousand people, 50 being due to disability and 827 to premature 
death. It was seen that premature death DALY (94 %) greatly outweighed 
disability DALY (6 %). The highest DALY values due to premature death in men 
were related to cancer of the stomach (169.8), leukaemia (106.8), colon and the 
rectum (100.4), lymphomas and multiple myelomas (89.9), whilst the highest 
values in women were observed in cervical (122.4), breast (121.9) and stomach 
cancer (94.2) and leukaemia (86.0). The types and cancer sites related to more 
years of life lost (YLL) were the colon and rectum (11.3), breast (6.2), liver 
(6.05) and cervical cancer (5.43).
CONCLUSIONS: The burden of disease from cancer in Santander in 2005 was mainly 
due to premature death YLL in both sexes and all age-groups.

