Genetic and environmental determinants of early vascular ageing (EVA).

Nilsson PM(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Clinical Sciences, Lund University, University Hospital, S-205 
02 Malmo, Sweden. Peter.Nilsson@med.lu.se

Cardiovascular disease is multidimensional and new ideas are needed to develop 
the conventional risk factor paradigm that has been based on the Framingham 
Heart Study since more than 30 years. Traditional risk factors such as 
hypertension, smoking, hyperlipidemia and diabetes can only explain about 50% of 
the distribution of coronary heart disease whereas the inclusion of new risk 
markers or protective markers may increase the explained proportion up to 80% of 
myocardial infarction risk according to the INTERHEART study. Still there are 
substantial differences in cardiovascular risk between regions and populations 
that are hard to explain. Findings in the former Soviet Union geographical area 
in Eastern Europe could contribute to new and better understanding of 
cardiovascular risk as a reflection of ageing in general, as populations in 
these areas not only run a very high cardiovascular risk but also have a shorter 
mean life expectancy in general. New understanding of the interaction between 
genes and the environment in prediction of cardiovascular ageing could 
contribute to the development of more effective preventive strategies.

